1) What does the void return type signify in a Java method?
-->👉 The void return type means:

The method does NOT return any value.

It performs an action only
No result is sent back to the caller
✅ Example
void display() {
    System.out.println("Hello");
}



2) Can a void method include a return statement? Explain with an example.
-->👉 Yes, but only without a value

return; → allowed (used to exit the method early)
return value; → ❌ not allowed
✅ Example
void check(int x) {
    if (x < 0) {
        return; // exits method
    }
    System.out.println("Positive number");
}




3) When should you use a void method instead of a method that returns a value?
-->👉 Use a void method when:

You only need to perform an action (printing, updating, etc.)
No result needs to be returned
✅ Examples:
Printing output
Updating object values
Logging or validation

4) Can a void method call another method that returns a value? Explain how.
-->👉 Yes, absolutely

    The returned value can be:
    Stored in a variable
    Used directly
    ✅ Example
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }
    
    void displaySum() {
        int result = add(10, 20); // calling non-void method
        System.out.println(result);
    }


5) What are the advantages and limitations of using void methods in Java?
-->✅ Advantages
    Simple and easy to use
    Good for actions/operations
    Improves readability for tasks like printing/logging
    ❌ Limitations
    Cannot return results
    Less reusable in calculations
    Cannot be used in expressions
